<div class="cover">
<h1>SL-301</h1>
<h2>Workflow State Engine<br>Complete Delivery &amp; Testing Report</h2>
<p class="meta"><strong>Project:</strong> OraBooks Lean MVP<br>
<strong>Report Date:</strong> 20 June 2026<br>
<strong>Document Version:</strong> 1.0</p>
<p><span class="status">STATUS: COMPLETE — MVP SIGN-OFF READY</span></p>
</div>

<h1 class="first">1. Executive Summary</h1>
<p>SL-301 delivers a <strong>central Workflow State Engine</strong> for OraBooks. Every business-record status change flows through a single entry point: <code>OraBooks_Workflow::transition()</code>. The engine validates transitions, locks database rows (FOR UPDATE), runs inside a DB transaction, writes audit logs, and publishes <code>state_transition</code> events.</p>
<p>Implementation covers <strong>five record types</strong> (journal, invoice, bill, expense, commission), <strong>three API surfaces</strong> (PHP, guarded AJAX, REST), RBAC/fiscal/MFA preconditions, observability metrics, and React UI including invoice cancel and bill void.</p>
<div class="box"><strong>Bottom Line:</strong> SL-301 is <strong>100% complete</strong> for Lean MVP sign-off. All 15 Definition of Done items are satisfied. The only intentional deferral is a dynamic <code>state_machine_config</code> database table (spec allows hard-coded machines for MVP).</div>

<h1>2. Problem Statement (Before SL-301)</h1>
<ul>
<li>Workflow status fields updated directly in module code — no single validation path</li>
<li>Inconsistent behaviour across journal, invoice, bill, expense modules</li>
<li>No unified audit trail for state changes</li>
<li>Race conditions possible under concurrent requests</li>
<li>Difficult tenant-scoped traceability</li>
<li>RBAC and fiscal guards scattered across callers</li>
</ul>

<h1>3. Solution Architecture</h1>
<p><strong>Flow:</strong> UI / AJAX / REST → Module method → <code>OraBooks_Workflow::transition()</code> → Validate → Preconditions (RBAC / MFA / Fiscal) → DB Transaction + FOR UPDATE → Update status → Persist transition log → COMMIT → Audit + Event Bus → Observability metrics.</p>
<h2>3.1 Core Design Principles</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Single write path</strong> — No production code updates workflow columns without <code>transition()</code></li>
<li><strong>Atomic transitions</strong> — START TRANSACTION, SELECT FOR UPDATE, validate, update, COMMIT or ROLLBACK</li>
<li><strong>Fail closed</strong> — Invalid transitions return HTTP 409 and log <code>invalid_state_transition</code></li>
<li><strong>Tenant traceability</strong> — <code>state_machine_transitions.org_id</code> on every row</li>
<li><strong>Extensibility</strong> — Hooks: <code>orabooks_workflow_preconditions</code>, <code>orabooks_workflow_after_transition</code></li>
</ul>

<h1>4. Delivery Phases (All Complete)</h1>
<table>
<tr><th>Phase</th><th>Scope</th><th>Status</th></tr>
<tr><td>Phase 0</td><td>Inventory, state matrices, migration backlog, DoD checklist</td><td class="done">Complete</td></tr>
<tr><td>Phase 1</td><td>Core engine: transactions, FOR UPDATE, hooks, AJAX, org_id column</td><td class="done">Complete</td></tr>
<tr><td>Phase 2</td><td>Caller migration — all 5 record types use transition()</td><td class="done">Complete</td></tr>
<tr><td>Phase 3</td><td>Events, RBAC/fiscal preconditions, observability, health AJAX</td><td class="done">Complete</td></tr>
<tr><td>Phase 4</td><td>Gap closure: cancel, void, expense lock, REST, MFA centralization</td><td class="done">Complete</td></tr>
</table>

<h1>5. State Machines — 100% Fully Wired</h1>

<h2>5.1 Journal (journals.status)</h2>
<p><strong>States:</strong> draft, review_pending, approved, posted, locked, reversed</p>
<p><strong>Transitions:</strong> submit, approve, reject, post, lock, reverse, edit</p>
<p><strong>Flow:</strong> draft → submit → review_pending → approve → approved → post → posted → lock → locked. Reject returns to draft. Reverse from posted/locked.</p>
<p><strong>Files:</strong> class-orabooks-posting.php, class-orabooks-approval.php. Post auto-chains lock.</p>

<h2>5.2 Invoice (invoices.workflow_status)</h2>
<p><strong>States:</strong> draft, sent, posted, cancelled</p>
<p><strong>Transitions:</strong> send, post, cancel — <strong>ALL WIRED end-to-end</strong></p>
<p><strong>Backend:</strong> send_invoice(), post_invoice(), cancel_invoice()</p>
<p><strong>AJAX:</strong> orabooks_invoice_send, orabooks_invoice_post, orabooks_invoice_cancel</p>
<p><strong>UI:</strong> /invoices — Send, Post, Pay, Cancel buttons</p>

<h2>5.3 Bill (bills.workflow_status)</h2>
<p><strong>States:</strong> draft, submitted, approved, posted, void</p>
<p><strong>Transitions:</strong> submit, approve, post, void — <strong>ALL WIRED end-to-end</strong></p>
<p><strong>Backend:</strong> submit_bill(), approve_bill(), post_bill(), void_bill()</p>
<p><strong>AJAX:</strong> orabooks_bill_submit, orabooks_bill_approve, orabooks_bill_post, orabooks_bill_void</p>
<p><strong>UI:</strong> /vendors — Submit, Approve, Post, Void buttons</p>

<h2>5.4 Expense (expenses.workflow_status)</h2>
<p><strong>States:</strong> draft, submitted, ai_review, approved, posted, locked</p>
<p><strong>Transitions:</strong> submit, ai_review, approve, reject, post, lock — <strong>ALL WIRED</strong></p>
<p>Post automatically chains lock transition (journal pattern).</p>
<p><strong>File:</strong> class-orabooks-expenses.php | <strong>UI:</strong> /expenses</p>

<h2>5.5 Commission (commissions_earned.status)</h2>
<p><strong>States:</strong> earned, paid, expired | <strong>Transitions:</strong> pay, expire — WIRED</p>
<p><strong>File:</strong> class-orabooks-commission.php | <strong>UI:</strong> /commissions</p>

